fields.physical_description:
1. main building; rectangular in shape; made from hard board painted beige. Front facade has a shallow wall flanking 2 rows of stairs each side (grey). Central part has a wall painted beige with white decoration. The front is heavily decorated; it has 2 elongated arched windows on either side with surrounds made from modelling clay painted white. In the centre of each window is a blue painted Star of David. In the front centre of the synagogue is a round window; surrounded by various white painted decoration-Menorahs-Torahs-Star of David-Hebrew Pointers? The main doorway is arched with a brown stained double wood door which is hinged; it opens into the Synagogue. Each side of the body has 3 elongated arched windows with white painted surrounds made from modelling clay on one side; a round window at the top and then 4 elongated arched windows. The back has 3 round windows along the top; a Star of David and a design of 2 lions; possibly Lions of Judas which support the two tablets on which the Ten Commandments are written. One of the sides is divided into 3; the middle partition is attached but the other two are hinged and open up; therefore making the contents more accessible. Entering the body; there is an entrance hall which is partitioned off from the main part. The floor is polished stained wood.
Inside the door is a sink of modelling clay which is a symbol of cleanliness. There is a double staircase with landing-with a golden coloured velvet carpet and then another row of steps which lead up to a stepped Gallery area. There are two hinged doors either side of the stairs which lead to the main body of the Synagogue. At the back of the main body is a central wooden plinth with a large bench or pew where the Rabbi sits; it is attached to the wall. In front there is a square raised area which is covered with a golden velvet carpet; wooden benches are on either side. At the front there is a wooden pew with hinged side doors; on either side there is a brass candle holder with 2 white wax candles. Round this central plinth are wooden benches with figures of male Jews worshipping. At the very front is the altar; ARK; made of stained and varnished wood attached to the wall with hinged doors. It is lined with gold velvet; inside the Scrolls (Torahs) are kept. Hanging from the front of the Ark is the everlasting light (Ner Tamid) which burns continuously. Placed on top is a silver plaque of the Ten Commandments. In front of the Ark is a wooden lectern (Bimah) where the Scroll which has been removed from the Ark is placed. On the wall beside the Ark; raised in relief; are 2 gold painted Menorahs and wheat sheaves. The inner walls of the Synagogue are painted white. Upstairs is a seated gallery with stained wooden benches on which the women of the congregation sit.

fields.title: MODEL
fields.history_note:
References: It consists of the main building and congregation with interior fittings. Congregation consists of the Rabbi; Cantor; women and men with skullcaps (kippot); fringed shawls (tallits); Tallit bags and prayer books (Siddur).

The body was made by David Green with some of the interior parts and congregation made by members of the Stamford Hill Jewish social club.  Ken (died Christmas 1995) and Muriel Gent made most of the bodies and heads, while the others did the decorations and dressing.
